// Proposed by 🏭 tart-ci. Defends specs/macos-ci/03-tart-ci-and-orchard.md and 04-tart-licensing-risk.md.
// 04 shipped with ZERO backing claims: the highest-risk numbers in the repo (a human signs off on them)
// were entirely unledgered. Every tier threshold below now has one.
//
// READ OQ-08 FIRST. The tart search index covers 20 DOC pages and ZERO blog posts, yet 04's three most
// load-bearing citations are blog posts that return HTTP 200. `doc-contains` reads the index, never the
// live page, so it reports a real page as "fabricated or moved" (STRUCTURE:). The `cli-help` + `curl`
// claims below are the workaround, dry-run PASSING. They grep RAW HTML, so a literal broken by an inline
// tag silently fails; every expect below was chosen to be tag-free and was verified.
// SECOND SHARP EDGE, found by dry-running rather than by reasoning: cli-help's check_contains is a bare
// `in` over raw output with NO whitespace normalization, while doc-contains runs norm_text (collapse +
// casefold). So an expect spanning an HTML source LINE-WRAP also fails. That is what broke
// tart-2023-post-defines-server-installation on the first pass. Keep curl expects SHORT.
//
// THE TWO must_fail CONTROLS BELOW WERE MUTATION-TESTED, not assumed (see OQ-19, harness's cross-audit of
// this role). Swapping each expect for a string the target DOES contain makes both flip to FAIL
// ("CONTROL PASSED -- the oracle is broken"). So neither is vacuous. A separate probe confirms /licensing/
// carries real body text (5,225 chars), closing OQ-19's zero-text hole for this file specifically.
// CONTROL-tart-blog-is-outside-doc-index-domain is doc-INDEX, which tests path membership and never reads
// body text, so the OQ-19 hole cannot reach it at all.
// CAVEAT, named in each claim: cli-help ignores curl's exit code (tools/verify_claims.py:225), so a
// network outage produces a FAIL, not an UNREACHABLE:. That is a false refutation, and it is why OQ-08
// asks 🔬 ledger for a `url-contains` kind.

