// ================= CROSS-AUDIT of secrets (13-build-secrets.md) =================
// The two must_fail/CONTROL pairs are SOUND, but the PACKER_LOG pair is UNDER-POWERED exactly as
// secrets says: its control matches a literal stdout prints identically with and without the overlay.
// CONFIRMED BY EXECUTION on separate pipes: stdout 136B == 136B (cmp clean); stderr 0B -> 845B.
// The successor claims below isolate stderr with `sh -c '... 2>&1 1>/dev/null'`, which cli-help can
// run because it spawns argv directly. Every network probe carries a FETCH_FAILED guard so an empty
// download cannot masquerade as a pass (cli-help ignores curl's exit code -- see OQ-08).
{"id": "CONTROL-packer-debug-log-stderr-emits-info-banner", "kind": "cli-help", "file": "specs/macos-ci/13-build-secrets.md", "argv": ["sh", "-c", "packer inspect tests/fixtures/packer-sensitive 2>&1 1>/dev/null"], "env": {"PACKER_LOG": "1"}, "expect": "[INFO] Packer version:", "claim": "DISCRIMINATOR + positive control. Isolates STDERR (2>&1 1>/dev/null) so stdout cannot satisfy it. Proves PACKER_LOG=1 really produced a debug log: 845B on stderr vs 0B without. Partner of packer-sensitive-hides-secret-in-isolated-debug-log."}
{"id": "CONTROL-packer-debug-log-stderr-prints-plain-literal", "kind": "cli-help", "file": "specs/macos-ci/13-build-secrets.md", "argv": ["sh", "-c", "packer inspect tests/fixtures/packer-sensitive 2>&1 1>/dev/null"], "env": {"PACKER_LOG": "1"}, "expect": "plain_FIXTURE_CONTROL", "claim": "POSITIVE CONTROL, same argv+env as packer-sensitive-hides-secret-in-isolated-debug-log: the debug log on stderr DOES carry non-sensitive literals, so 'the secret is absent from stderr' is not satisfied by an empty stderr. REFINES 13:297, which says plain_FIXTURE_CONTROL 'appears on stdout' -- it appears on BOTH streams under the overlay."}
{"id": "packer-sensitive-hides-secret-in-isolated-debug-log", "kind": "cli-help", "must_fail": true, "file": "specs/macos-ci/13-build-secrets.md", "argv": ["sh", "-c", "packer inspect tests/fixtures/packer-sensitive 2>&1 1>/dev/null"], "env": {"PACKER_LOG": "1"}, "expect": "ghp_FIXTURE_SENTINEL", "claim": "The sensitive value is absent from the DEBUG LOG ITSELF, not merely from a stdout+stderr blob that stdout could have satisfied alone. This is the properly-powered successor to packer-sensitive-hides-secret-under-debug-log, whose control (CONTROL-packer-debug-log-prints-plain-literals) matches a literal that stdout prints identically with and without the overlay. Paired with CONTROL-packer-debug-log-stderr-emits-info-banner (log exists) and CONTROL-packer-debug-log-stderr-prints-plain-literal (stream non-empty)."}
{"id": "packer-no-debug-log-on-stderr-when-overlay-disabled", "kind": "cli-help", "file": "specs/macos-ci/13-build-secrets.md", "argv": ["sh", "-c", "test -z \"$(packer inspect tests/fixtures/packer-sensitive 2>&1 1>/dev/null)\" && echo NO_DEBUG_LOG_ON_STDERR"], "env": {"PACKER_LOG": "0"}, "expect": "NO_DEBUG_LOG_ON_STDERR", "claim": "PACKER_LOG=0 => stderr is EMPTY (0 bytes), so the overlay is what CAUSES the debug log. Written as a POSITIVE assertion (echoes a token) rather than a bare must_fail, because 'no [INFO] line' is also satisfied by no output at all. env pins '0' rather than omitting the key: cli-help merges env over os.environ and cannot UNSET (OQ-14)."}
{"id": "packer-log-value-off-still-enables-logging", "kind": "cli-help", "file": "specs/macos-ci/13-build-secrets.md", "argv": ["sh", "-c", "packer inspect tests/fixtures/packer-sensitive 2>&1 1>/dev/null"], "env": {"PACKER_LOG": "off"}, "expect": "[INFO] Packer version:", "claim": "Backs 13:316. PACKER_LOG is NOT parsed as a boolean: the literal string 'off' ENABLES debug logging. Only unset, '' and '0' disable it; 'off', 'false', 'no', '00' and ' ' all enable. An operator who 'turned logging off' with PACKER_LOG=off has turned it ON."}
{"id": "packer-shell-use-env-var-file-has-no-default-assignment", "kind": "cli-help", "file": "specs/macos-ci/13-build-secrets.md", "argv": ["sh", "-c", "f=$(curl -fsSL https://raw.githubusercontent.com/hashicorp/packer/v1.15.4/provisioner/shell/provisioner.go); printf '%s' \"$f\" | grep -q 'UseEnvVarFile bool' || { echo FETCH_FAILED; exit 0; }; printf '%s' \"$f\" | grep -qE 'UseEnvVarFile[[:space:]]*=[^=]' && echo HAS_DEFAULT_ASSIGNMENT || echo NO_DEFAULT_ASSIGNMENT"], "expect": "NO_DEFAULT_ASSIGNMENT", "claim": "SETTLES ledger's OQ-09. packer v1.15.4 provisioner/shell/provisioner.go declares `UseEnvVarFile bool` (:46) and NEVER assigns it -- it is only READ via `== true` (:103, :110, :241). So `use_env_var_file` defaults to Go's zero value, false. The DOCS page never states this default (it states one for skip_clean and not for use_env_var_file), so 13:174's `# default` was an inference until now. Guarded against a silent network failure: the probe first requires `UseEnvVarFile bool` to be present and echoes FETCH_FAILED otherwise, so an empty download CANNOT satisfy the expect."}
{"id": "packer-shell-varfile-is-chmod-0600-in-guest", "kind": "cli-help", "file": "specs/macos-ci/13-build-secrets.md", "argv": ["sh", "-c", "f=$(curl -fsSL https://raw.githubusercontent.com/hashicorp/packer/v1.15.4/provisioner/shell/provisioner.go); printf '%s' \"$f\" | grep -q 'UseEnvVarFile bool' || { echo FETCH_FAILED; exit 0; }; printf '%s' \"$f\" | grep -o 'chmod 0600 %s' | head -1"], "expect": "chmod 0600 %s", "claim": "Backs 13:90. The uploaded env-var file is chmod 0600 on the guest (provisioner.go:279). 0600 protects it from other guest users; it does NOT protect it from `strings` on the host's disk image, which is the whole point of 13. Same FETCH_FAILED guard as packer-shell-use-env-var-file-has-no-default-assignment."}
